%text \textbf{Basic Identities}
The following trigonometric identities are fundamental. We are not giving proofs for them here. But you should \underline\text{commit these to memory}.
%
\begin{align} \sin (A+B) &= \sin A\cdot \cos B + \cos A\cdot \sin B \\ \sin (A-B) &= \sin A\cdot \cos B - \cos A\cdot \sin B \\ \cos (A + B) &= \cos A \cdot \cos B - \sin A\cdot \sin B \\ \cos (A-B) &= \cos A\cdot \cos B + \sin A\cdot \sin B \\ \tan (A+B) &= \dfrac{\tan A + \tan B}{1-\tan A\cdot \tan B} \\ \tan (A-B) &= \dfrac{\tan A - \tan B}{1+ \tan A\cdot \tan B} \end{align}
%text
\textbf{Derieved Identities}
The following identities are simply \underline\text{specific cases} of the basic identities above
% \begin{align} \sin 2A &= \sin (A+A) = 2\sin A\cdot \cos A \\ \sin 3A &= \sin (2A + A) = 3\sin A - 4\sin^3 A \\ \cos 2A &= \cos (A+A) = \cos^2 A - \sin^2 A \\ \cos 3A &= 4\cos^3 A - 3\cos A \\ \tan 2A &= \dfrac{2\tan A}{1-\tan^2 A} \\ \tan 3A &= \dfrac{3\tan A - \tan^3 A}{1-3\tan^2 A} \end{align}
